            <![CDATA[
                    <p><img src="https://rudytrnka.com/media/posts/28/ComfyUI_00453_.png" class="type:primaryImage" alt="" /></p>
                <div class="gallery-wrapper"><div class="gallery" data-is-empty="false" data-translation="Add images" data-columns="2">
<figure class="gallery__item"><a href="https://rudytrnka.com/media/posts/28/gallery/ComfyUI_00453_.png" data-size="1224x1688"><img loading="lazy" src="https://rudytrnka.com/media/posts/28/gallery/ComfyUI_00453_-thumbnail.png" alt="" width="768" height="1059"></a></figure>
<figure class="gallery__item"><a href="https://rudytrnka.com/media/posts/28/gallery/scan0022.jpg" data-size="1648x2250"><img loading="lazy" src="https://rudytrnka.com/media/posts/28/gallery/scan0022-thumbnail.jpg" alt="" width="768" height="1049"></a></figure>
</div></div>
<p>Every artist at one point or another has done some form of graffiti art style. I choose Presto a very long time ago as my graffiti name to develop and design with. When you try to draw the same word over and over trying to improve, or just to create a new version, this process is the equivalent to going to a gym to workout your body, except this process is a workout for your mind. I am excited every time I give AI one of my original works of art, sitting with anticipation waiting less then a minute to see a simple line artwork turned into a full color piece. I did not give much guidance to AI to learn how it thinks before taking full control of the direction. </p>
            ]]>
        </content>
